Cross River State Government has ordered the returned of five truck loaded with almajiris including other passengers back to the northern part of the country. A border patrol team, comprising Peace Corp members, civilian vigilantes, COVID-19 border taskforce, and youth groups etc had intercepted the trucks on Wednesday night at the Garkem border town in Bekwara LGA of the state near Benue State. The team leader, Signor Omang Idiege, who is Commissioner for Youths, said it was as a result of intensive search and blockade of interstate vehicular travels, led his team to intercept the trucks. “After a thorough check on the five trucks, we discovered that most of the passengers, aside goods, were almajiris who did not meet COVID-19 protocols, we had to force them to return”. He appealed to the Chairman, COVID-19 to visit the truck parks in the state and caution their drivers against indulging conveying almajiris who have not been isolated. State security adviser, Dr Alfred Mboto, said his officers at the scene have briefed him about the development, “We got a report from our security and taskforce teams at the Garkem border town on Wednesday night that trucks carrying large number of children from the north alleged to be almajiris were intercepted after thorough check, and have been turned back.” COVID-19: Residents panic as truck dumps Almajiris from Sokoto in Ondo COVID-19: Police frustrating our fight against Coronavirus - Ondo Government COVID-19: Northern elders sending Almajiris infected with Coronavirus to South East - Ohanaeze alleges